The clacks and chinks of the coal yard faded away by the time Matthis reached the square. The rain picked up again. Puddles formed in the square. He dug his foot in the mud, and the puddles drained away from the nearby buildings and poured in a wide sheet toward the gallows. Matthis felt the black skeleton better than he saw it.

A bundle of blankets were piled under the eaves of the church. Roof water streamed onto it. Matthis cocked his head. Perhaps a donation hadn't made it inside. Matthis bent and reached to scoop up the wet pile. The pile of blankets jumped when he touched it. A woman's head emerged from the blanket folds.

Matthis straightened. "Nell," he said. "What are you doing here?"

Her hair hung from her head in stringy knots. Her eyes were red and puffy. A wave of icy water fell from the church eaves and splattered on her head. She didn't acknowledge it. She shivered and fumbled around blindly with one hand. She pulled a dirty handkerchief from somewhere in the blankets. It may once have been white. She daubed her eyes with it and settled back into the blankets.

Matthis knelt beside her and shook her shoulder. "Nell. Please answer me."

She smacked her lips, her eyes still closed. She nuzzled her face into the wet blankets. Her deep breaths rose and fell. Matthis touched her forehead. He felt the spot under her ear and along her jaw. Nothing unusual.

Matthis sucked his cheek. He shook rainwater from his hair. He stood and looked down at the girl. He crossed his arms.

Then he nodded. He bent down and scooped Nell into his arms. Her bones duck hard into his arms. She snorted in her sleep and nestled her head into his shoulder. She was much too light.

His back straight and legs steady, Matthis pointed himself toward the Oak and Ember.

--

Aura sat outside the Oak and Ember. She tossed a pebble into a puddle in the grass. She tossed another.

Matthis froze.

Rainwater didn't touch her. It fell in a circle around her. He could see the droplets splash in the shape of a dome above her. But nothing was there. She tossed another pebble, and the water met an invisible barrier before it reached her.

Elspeth opened the door. She wiped her hands on her apron. Matthis expected her to exclaim. Surely she could see this odd magic. But Elspeth stood beside the girl and tossed her own pebble into the grass. The water splashed Elspeth. Somehow, Aura hadn't gotten wet at all. Elspeth said something in Aura's ear and gestured at something above the girl's head. Elspeth reached up and touched the water on the invisible dome. Matthis saw her smile and pat Aura's back. The little girl nodded and tossed one more rock into the grass.

The invisible dome vanished. As if thrown from a bucket, a layer of water landed on them both. Matthis heard a squeal of laughter over the rain. They were smiling. Elspeth made exaggerated shooing motions, a broad smile on her face. Aura bounced into the pub.

His feet moved before he realized. Matthis drifted after them and stopped before the door. Nell shifted in his arms and sighed. Her red eyes remained closed. Matthis gritted his teeth and stepped inside.

Elspeth's humming warmed the pub as well as the fire. His vision blocked by blankets, Matthis toed the benches and stepped around them toward the hearth.

Elspeth emerged from the kitchen with her hands in her apron. Their eyes met, and Elspeth sprang into action. She pulled a wooden chair from one corner of the room and dragged it in front of the fire. Matthis placed Nelly into it. He propped her upright and laid her head on the chair's back. Elspeth tore the blankets away and bundled them into Matthis' arms.

"Clothesline," she said. 

Matthis was already on his way. He closed the pub door, rounded the pub, spread the blankets onto a wire strung between two trees, and dashed back inside.

On her knees, her brows furrowed, Elspeth was patting Nell's cheek and calling her name when he opened the door. The maid shook her head and groaned, her swollen eyes still closed. Aura had buried her face into Elspeth's apron.

"Wool blanket," said Elspeth to Matthis without looking up, "upstairs."

Matthis wound through the kitchen, which smelled of herbs and bread, and up a tight staircase. The smell of the wooden stairs brought back memories of Beorn, Elspeth's father. He found three rooms at the top of the stairs. Without hesitation, he ducked into Elspeth's room and drew out a heavy wool blanket. He surprised himself. It had been years since he had last been up here.

Nell lifted her head when he returned. She blinked and rubbed her eyes. She asked where she was. Color returned to Elspeth's cheeks.

"The Oak and Ember?" said Nell. "I'm so knackered, I thought it were the Flagon."

Nell thanked him when Matthis wrapped her in the blanket. Aura whimpered into Elspeth's apron. Nell laid her head back and nestled into the blanket. Matthis and Elspeth looked at each other.

The fire crackled. Matthis tossed another block onto it. The hearth spat sparks up the flue.

"How is Aura adjusting?" said Matthis. He lifted the poker and stoked the fire. 

"She's playing now." Elspeth bent down and hugged Aura. The tiny girl cried quietly into her chest. "But she still hasn't said a word."

Matthis grunted at glanced at them. He thought he saw something, a small haze or glow around them. But he decided he imagined it.

"Sorry to be such a bother," said Nell.

"Stop that, Nell," said Elspeth. She lifted Aura and took her upstairs. "You can stay as long as you like. And," she added over her shoulder, "Matthis is the one who brought you."

Nell looked up at him. Matthis placed an arm on the back of the chair. 

"Thank you, Matthis."

He crouched next to her. She looked away. 

"What happened," he said.

Nell swallowed. Her face turned red. She looked at the ceiling. With a long exhale, she closed her eyes. Matthis waited. Nell bit her lip. 

"I ... I left the Flagon."

Matthis nodded, unsurprised. Elspeth returned from upstairs. She tightened her hair kerchief. Matthis shared a look with her.

"I'm sorry. I been such a bother," Nell whispered. She screwed her eyes shut. Her body stiffened under the blankets.

"I want you to stay, Nell," said Elspeth, her voice soft and tender, "as long as you like."

"I can't -- that's too much to ask --"

"Elspeth is taking care of the girl, Aura," said Matthis. "She could use your help."

Elspeth smiled at him. "And if any of my customers touches you," she added to Nell, "tell me, and I'll teach him."

Nell gaped and looked between them. "You ... you want me? Little old me?"

Elspeth looked at Matthis when she replied. 

"Yeah. Yeah we do."